Title:
Tutorial example  - demonstration of mixed gauge

Same physical problem as tutorial/10IRSpectrum

We demonstrate the use of mixed gauge,
which is of disadvantage for the given problem, but
an important ingredient of the haCC method

#define BOX 20
#define RG 20
#define RC BOX

Surface: points
RC

Spectrum: radialPoints=100,plot=total

# NOTE: in mixed gauge, need more angular momenta
Axis: name,nCoefficients,lower end, upper end,functions,order
 Phi,1
 Eta,25,-1,1, assocLegendre{Phi}
 Rn,48, 0.,BOX,polynomial,12
 Rn,20, BOX,Infty,polExp[0.5]

Absorption: kind, axis, theta, upper
ECS,Rn,0.3,BOX

# potential in the Hamiltonian - as in 1d, we clip the Coulomb tail off

Operator: hamiltonian='1/2<<Laplacian>>-<1><1><trunc[15,20]/Q>'

# the mixed gauge operator, where length gauge is used up to Rg=RG
# very ugly operator, therefore pre-defined for polar coordinates
Operator: interaction=<<MixedGaugeDipole:Rg=RG>>

# the corresponding velocity gauge operator
# Operator: interaction='iLaserA0[t]<<D/DZ>>'

Operator: expectationValue='<1><1><chi[0,20]>,<1><1><chi[15,20]>'

Laser: shape, I(W/cm2), FWHM, lambda(nm)
cos2, 1.e14, 2. OptCyc, 800.

TimePropagation: end,print,store,cutEnergy,accuracy
6 OptCyc, 0.05 OptCyc,0.5 au,100,1.e-7
